# Feature Spec Format Reference

This document defines the format for Feature Specs in `{{base_dir}}/specs/features/`. Feature Specs are **living documents** that accumulate User Stories and requirements across multiple changes. User Stories are the core organizational unit; REQ IDs serve as engineering traceability sub-items.

---

## Purpose

A Feature Spec is the **single source of truth** for WHAT a feature does and WHY it exists. It answers "what value does this deliver to users?" while `ai-knowledge/` answers "how does it currently work?". When both agree, the system is healthy.

---

## Naming Convention

Name files by **user-facing feature**, not by implementation module:

| Feature Name | Covers |
|-------------|--------|
| `sdd-workflow.md` | Story, Plan, Tasks, Archive, Verify, Fast-Forward |
| `ai-knowledge.md` | Knowledge Init, Generate, Update, Quality Gate |
| `project-setup.md` | CLI, Init, Steering, Config, Base Directory |
| `agent-integration.md` | Agent Sync, Skill Generation, Progressive Disclosure |
| `design-phase.md` | Generate Mode, Extract Mode, Platform Adapters |

New features can be added as the product grows.

---

## Standard Format

### 1. Frontmatter

```yaml
---
feature: {feature-slug}
status: active
last_updated: {YYYY-MM-DD}
story_count: {N}
req_count: {N}
---
```

### 2. Title + Who & Why

```markdown
# {Feature Title}

## Who & Why

**服務對象**: [Target users]

**解決問題**: [Problem being solved]

**為什麼重要**: [Why this feature matters — value proposition]
```

### 3. User Stories & Behavior Specifications

User Stories are the **primary organizational unit**. REQ IDs appear as sub-items under the Story they implement.

```markdown
## User Stories & Behavior Specifications

### US-NNN: {Story Title} [{Priority}]

{As a [role],}
{I want [capability],}
{So that [value].}

**Acceptance Scenarios:**
- WHEN {condition} THEN {expected behavior}
- WHEN {condition} THEN {expected behavior}

#### REQ-{MODULE}-{NNN}: {Requirement Title}
{Brief description of the system behavior.}

**Scenarios:**
- WHEN {condition}, THEN {expected behavior}
- WHEN {condition}, THEN {expected behavior}

---
```

### 4. Edge Cases

```markdown
## Edge Cases

- {Edge case}: {Expected behavior}
- {Edge case}: {Expected behavior}
```

### 5. Success Criteria

```markdown
## Success Criteria

- **SC-1**: {Measurable outcome}
- **SC-2**: {Measurable outcome}
```

### 6. Maintenance Rules

Every Feature Spec must include these rules:

```markdown
## Maintenance Rules

1. **Replace-in-Place**: MODIFIED User Stories and REQs directly replace existing versions
2. **Functional Grouping**: New requirements insert under the corresponding User Story
3. **No Inline Provenance**: Historical attribution only in Change History table
4. **Deprecation over Deletion**: Removed requirements move to Deprecated section
```

### 7. Deprecated Requirements

```markdown
## Deprecated Requirements

_(None)_
```

When requirements are removed, move them here with removal reason and date.

### 8. Change History

```markdown
## Change History

| Date | Change | Impact | Stories/REQs |
|------|--------|--------|-------------|
| {date} | {change-name} | {brief description} | US-NNN, REQ-XXX-NNN |
```

---

## File Length Guidelines

- Keep under **300 lines** per Feature Spec
- If a Feature Spec exceeds 300 lines, consider splitting into sub-features
- User Stories section should occupy **40%+** of total content (not REQ-dominated)

